Microstate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
microstate
\emph default
 is defined by specifying completely the microscopic state of a system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Example 1
\emph default
: Let the system be a group of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 dices.
 Hence the microstate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is defined upon assigning the values 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\in\left\{ 1,2,\ldots,6\right\} $
\end_inset

 to each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 dices.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r & =\left(n_{1},n_{2},\ldots,n_{N}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

The possible number of microstates is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Omega\left(N\right) & =6^{N}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Example 2
\emph default
: Let the system be a physical system with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 We consider a 
\emph on
closed system
\emph default
, such that the associated Hamilton function/operator does not depend on
 time.
 In this case the Hamilton function/operator yields the 
\emph on
energy
\emph default
 of the microstate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Quantum mechanical case
\emph default
: As microstates we choose the eigenstates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \KET r\right\} $
\end_inset

 of the Hamilton operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}$
\end_inset

 determined by the time independent Schrödinger equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{H}\KET r & =E_{r}\KET r
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{r}$
\end_inset

 is the energy of the microstate.
 For a system with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom the eigenstates depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 quantum numbers:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r & =\left(n_{1},n_{2},\ldots,n_{f}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\emph on
Note
\emph default
: We assumed here that the closed system is restricted to a finite volume
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, such that the quantum numbers are discrete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Ideal gas of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 particles in a box of volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset


\emph default
: The interaction between gas particles is neglected (ideal gas).
 The total Hamilton operator is the sum of the Hamilton operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

-th particle:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{H} & =\sum_{\nu=1}^{N}\hat{h}_{\nu}=\sum_{\nu=1}^{N}\frac{\hat{p}_{\nu}^{2}}{2m}\label{eq:Hamiltonian-ideal-gas}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Specifically, it holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\hat{h}_{\nu}\KET s_{\nu} & =\varepsilon_{\nu}\left(s\right)\KET s_{\nu}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In the position representation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{s,\nu}\left(\vec{r}\right) & =\BraKet{\vec{r}|s}_{\nu}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\nabla^{2}\psi_{s,\nu}\left(\vec{r}\right) & =\varepsilon_{\nu}\left(s\right)\psi_{s,\nu}\left(\vec{r}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For a particle in a box, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{s,\nu}\left(\vec{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 vanishes at the boundaries.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $V=L^{3}$
\end_inset

 it holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\psi_{s,\nu}\left(0,y,z\right)=\psi_{s,\nu}\left(x,0,z\right)=\psi_{s,\nu}\left(x,y,0\right)\\
0 & =\psi_{s,\nu}\left(L,y,z\right)=\psi_{s,\nu}\left(x,L,z\right)=\psi_{s,\nu}\left(x,y,L\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This gives for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\nu x},\, n_{\nu y},\, n_{\nu z}\in\mathbb{N}_{\ge1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\begin{array}{rl}
{\displaystyle \psi_{s,\nu}\left(\vec{r}\right)} & {\displaystyle =A\sin\left(\frac{n_{\nu x}\pi x}{L}\right)\sin\left(\frac{n_{\nu y}\pi y}{L}\right)\sin\left(\frac{n_{\nu z}\pi z}{L}\right)}\\
{\displaystyle \varepsilon_{\nu}\left(s\right)} & {\displaystyle =\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\left(\frac{\pi}{L}\right)^{2}\left(n_{\nu x}^{2}+n_{\nu y}^{2}+n_{\nu z}^{2}\right)}
\end{array}\label{eq:Energy-ideal-gas}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Therefore the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\KET s_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{\nu}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 are fixed by the quantum numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\nu x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\nu y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\nu z}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the microstate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 of the system of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 atoms is defined by assigning the 
\begin_inset Formula $3N$
\end_inset

 quantum numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\left(n_{1},n_{2},\ldots,n_{3N}\right)$
\end_inset

 with the following order:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(n_{1},n_{2},n_{3}\right) & =\left(n_{1x},n_{1y},n_{1z}\right)\\
\left(n_{4},n_{5},n_{6}\right) & =\left(n_{2x},n_{2y},n_{2z}\right)\\
 & \ \ \vdots
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\emph on
Note
\emph default
: There are infinitely many microstates 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 as each quantum number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k}$
\end_inset

 can take infinitely many values.
 However, for 
\emph on
fixed energy
\emph default
, the number becomes 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
.
\emph on

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Note
\emph default
: 
\emph on
Phase-space volume per quantum state
\emph default

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The available states can be represented on a three-dimensional lattice in
 the space of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ p_{x},p_{y},p_{z}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\frac{\hbar\pi}{L}n_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Due to 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}>0$
\end_inset

, all 
\emph on
distinct
\emph default
 points are within the octant with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}>0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\color green
