\color inherit

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The number of states in a shell with radii between 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\sqrt{p_{x}^{2}+p_{y}^{2}+p_{z}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p+\dd p$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{8}\cdot\frac{4\pi p^{2}\dd p}{\left(\frac{\hbar\pi}{L}\right)^{3}} & =\frac{4\pi p^{2}\dd p}{h^{3}}V
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In general, the number of states with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\left(p\right)\le\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{V}{h^{3}}\cdot4\pi\int_{0}^{p_{m}}p^{2}\dd p & =\frac{1}{h^{3}}\cdot\int_{V}\dd^{3}r\int_{p\le p_{m}}\dd^{3}p
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So the minimal volume in phase space is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\hbar=h$
\end_inset

.
\emph on

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Note
\emph default
: Consider the free particle with periodic boundary conditions.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi\left(x\right) & =Ae^{\ii kx} & \psi\left(0\right) & =\psi\left(L\right)\quad\Rightarrow\quad k=\frac{2\pi n}{L} & n & \in\mathbb{Z}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Because 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x},\, p_{y},\, p_{z}$
\end_inset

 can now assume both positive and negative values, one has to consider a
 full sphere.
 In this case the infinitesimal number of states is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{4\pi p^{2}\dd p}{\left(\hbar\frac{2\pi}{L}\right)^{3}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Again the minimal volume in phase space is 
\begin_inset Formula $h=2\pi\hbar$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Classical case
\emph default
: In the classical case, a system with 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom is characterized by assigning the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 generalized coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1},q_{2},\ldots,q_{f}$
\end_inset

 as well as generalized impulses 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2},\ldots,p_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence there are 
\begin_inset Formula $2f$
\end_inset

 microstates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r & =\left(q_{1},\ldots,q_{f},p_{1},\ldots,p_{f}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For an ideal classical gas of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 particles there are 
\begin_inset Formula $2f=6N$
\end_inset

 microstates and a microstate is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r & =\left(\vec{r}_{1},\,\vec{r}_{2},\ldots,\vec{r}_{N}\,,\vec{p}_{1}\,,\vec{p}_{2},\ldots,\vec{p}_{N}\right)=\left(x_{1},\, y_{1},\, z_{1},\, x_{2},\ldots,z_{N},\, p_{x1},\, p_{y1},\, p_{z1},\ldots,p_{zN}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The energy is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left(q_{1},\, q_{2},\ldots,q_{f},\, p_{1},\ldots,p_{f}\right)$
\end_inset


\emph on
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Phase space
\emph default
: The 
\begin_inset Formula $2f$
\end_inset

-dimensional space spanned by the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ q_{1},p_{1},\ldots\right\} $
\end_inset

 is called phase-space.
 So to each classical microstate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is associated a point in phase-space.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


