\end_inset

For a statistical description we need to be able to 
\emph on
enumerate
\emph default
 the number of microstates 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 To this extent we observe that in general it is neither necessary nor possible
 to give the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q_{i},p_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 exactly.
 According to the uncertainty principle it holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\fbox{\ensuremath{{\displaystyle \Delta q\Delta p\ge\frac{\hbar}{2}}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

We count thus the number of classical states upon observing that for the
 quantum case to one state corresponds a surface 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in phase space.
 With the 
\begin_inset Formula $2f$
\end_inset

-dimensional phase space volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{ps}$
\end_inset

 the number of states is therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
N_{\text{states}} & =\frac{V_{ps}}{h^{f}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

