\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Macrostate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a many-particle-system with a very large number 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of particles, the number of microstates with the same energy is also very
 large.
 The system will constantly perform transitions 
\begin_inset Formula $r\to r'$
\end_inset

 between (accessible) microstates.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In general we are not interested to know details of the evolution of a microstat
e.
 Rather we are interested in:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

label=
\backslash
Roman*)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph on
Which
\emph default
 are the accessible microstates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
What
\emph default
 is the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{r}$
\end_inset

 of occurrence of the microstate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
macrostate
\emph default
 is the state of a system defined only through the set of probabilities
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{r}$
\end_inset

 for every configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\{ P_{r}\right\}  & =\left\{ P_{1},P_{2},\ldots\right\} 
\end{align}

\end_inset

These probabilities are defined according to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DefProbability"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P_{r} & =\lim_{M\to\infty}\frac{M_{r}}{M}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here one has 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 identical systems and the microstate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 occurs upon measurement 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{r}$
\end_inset

 times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Fundamental postulate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider a closed system.
 From experience we know that independent of the initial preparation, a
 closed system will evolve after some time to a certain macrostate, which
 is called 
\emph on
equilibrium state
\emph default
.
 The 
\emph on
macroscopically measurable quantities
\emph default
 are those, that attain 
\emph on
constant
\emph default
 values, which are typically averages of a microscopic quantity over all
 particles.
 The 
\emph on
fundamental postulate
\emph default
 states:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

A closed system in equilibrium is with equal probability in any of its accessibl
e microstates.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (ergodic hypothesis)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(This is due to the chaotic behavior of practically any system of many particles.
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Note
\emph default
: The fundamental postulate defines the connection between the microscopic
 structure, i.e.
 the accessible microstates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ r\right\} $
\end_inset

, and macroscopic quantities of the equilibrium state, i.e.
 the probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ P_{r}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Example 1
\emph default
: System of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 dices
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The number of accessible states is 
\begin_inset Formula $6^{N}$
\end_inset

, so the probability for each is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P_{r} & =\frac{1}{6^{N}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Example 2
\emph default
: Four electrons in a magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The relevant degrees of freedom are the spin 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{z}$
\end_inset

 of each electron along the quantization axis defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}=B\vec{e}_{z}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\hat{L}_{i} & =-\hat{\vec{\mu_{i}}}\cdot\vec{B} & \hat{\vec{\mu_{i}}} & =-\mu_{B}g\frac{\hat{\vec{s_{i}}}}{\hbar}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So a microstate is characterized by 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\left(s_{z,1},\, s_{z,2},\, s_{z,3},\, s_{z,4}\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{z,j}\in\pm\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Its energy is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E_{r} & =2\mu_{B}B\sum_{j=1}^{4}s_{z,j}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Suppose that the energy in the equilibrium state is 
\begin_inset Formula $E=2\mu_{B}B$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The accessible states (for distinguishable spins, e.g.
 sitting on a lattice) are (denoting 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{z}=\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\uparrow$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{z}=-\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\downarrow$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r & \in\left\{ \left(\uparrow\uparrow\uparrow\downarrow\right),\,\left(\uparrow\uparrow\downarrow\uparrow\right),\,\left(\uparrow\downarrow\uparrow\uparrow\right),\,\left(\downarrow\uparrow\uparrow\uparrow\right)\right\} =:M
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For example you can't find 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\uparrow\uparrow\uparrow\uparrow\right)$
\end_inset

, because this state has a different energy.
 The fundamental postulate yields the probability:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P_{r} & =\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{4} & \text{for }r\in M\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Alternative formulation of the fundamental postulate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 be the number of accessible states.
 Then the fundamental postulate can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P_{r} & =\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{\Omega} & \text{for accessible microstates}\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a closed system, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 depends on the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and a family 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 additional external parameters.
 For this one writes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Omega & =\Omega\left(E,x\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

and calls 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 the 
\emph on
microcanonical partition function
\emph default
.
 For a Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H=H\left(q,p,x\right)$
\end_inset

, the Hamilton operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}=\hat{H}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, so in general the energies 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{r}=E_{r}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 also depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 For example for a gas of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 atoms in a box of volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left(V,N\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 can be assigned only with some uncertainty 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta E$
\end_inset

, the partition function is the number of microstates with energies 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{r}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(E-\delta E,\, E\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Omega\left(E,x\right) & =\sum_{\sr{}r{E-\delta E\le E_{r}\left(x\right)\le E}}1
\end{align}

\end_inset

This yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P_{r}\left(E,x\right) & =\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{\Omega\left(E,x\right)} & E-\delta E\le E_{r}\left(x\right)\le E\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\label{eq:microcanonical-partition-function}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Partition function of the ideal gas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The external variables are 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left(V,N\right)$
\end_inset

.
 These are 
\emph on
extensive
\emph default
 variables, i.e.
 if you take two of the system and consider them together, these variables
 double, in contrast to 
\emph on
intensive
\emph default
 variables, which stay the same.
 We now proceed with the following steps:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{H}\left(V,N\right) & \xrightarrow{\text{1.}}\varepsilon_{r}\left(V,N\right)\xrightarrow{\text{2.}}\Omega\left(E,V,N\right)\xrightarrow{\text{3.}}\ln\left(\Omega\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Step 1: Eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}\left(V,N\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Form 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Hamiltonian-ideal-gas"

\end_inset

 we know:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\hat{H}\left(V,N\right) & =\sum_{\nu=1}^{N}\hat{h}_{\nu}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So for a microstate 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\left(n_{1},\ldots,n_{3N}\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k}\in\mathbb{N}_{\ge1}$
\end_inset

 we have from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Energy-ideal-gas"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E_{r}\left(V,N\right) & =\sum_{\nu=1}^{3N}\frac{p_{\nu}^{2}}{2m}=\sum_{\nu=1}^{3N}\frac{\pi^{2}\hbar^{2}n_{\nu}^{2}}{2mL^{2}}\label{eq:energy-ideal-gas}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Indistinguishability of particles
\emph default
: When evaluating properties of the ideal gas, we should account for the
 fact that in quantum mechanics, upon exchanging particles, the wave function
 changes at most its sign due to the particles indistinguishability, i.e.
 an exchange of two particles yields the 
\emph on
same state
\emph default
.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In general for a given microstate 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\left(n_{1},\ldots,n_{3N}\right)$
\end_inset

 one can generate 
\begin_inset Formula $N!$
\end_inset

 representations of the 
\emph on
same
\emph default
 macrostate upon exchange of particle indices.
 Thus when counting states, we have to take care, not to count the same
 microstate more than once.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Step 2: Evaluation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\left(E,V,N\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we introduce:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\phi\left(E,V,N\right) & :=\sum_{\sr{}r{E_{r}\left(V,N\right)\le E}}1
\end{align}

\end_inset

Given this, we can calculate the partition function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Omega\left(E,V,N\right) & =\phi\left(E\right)-\phi\left(E-\delta E\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

Hence we focus on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi\left(E\right) & =\underbrace{\sum_{n_{1}}\sum_{n_{2}}\ldots\sum_{n_{3N}}}_{E_{r}\le E}\frac{1}{N!}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N!}$
\end_inset

