\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset Formula $G=G\left(T,P,N\right)$
\end_inset

 follows, because 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is an extensive quantity and among 
\begin_inset Formula $T,P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 only 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is extensive:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G & =N\cdot g\left(T,P\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dG"

\end_inset

 follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mu & =\frac{\partial G\left(T,P,N\right)}{\partial N}=g\left(T,P\right)=\frac{G}{N}\nonumber \\
\Rightarrow\quad G & =N\mu\label{eq:G_Nmu}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Moreover holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\dd N+N\dd\mu=\dd G & \stackrel{\eqref{eq:gibbs_enthalpy}}{=}-S\dd T+V\dd P+\mu\dd N\\
\Rightarrow\qquad\dd\mu & =-\frac{S}{N}\dd T+\frac{V}{N}\dd P:=-s\dd T+v\dd P
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is the 
\emph on
Duhem-Gibbs relation
\emph default
 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\mu\left(P,T\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The equilibrium condition demands 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 to be minimal.
