\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Second law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Closed system
\emph default
: We have demonstrated that a closed system tends to an equilibrium situation,
 whereby the entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 acquires its maximal value.
 So in a process 
\begin_inset Formula $a\to b$
\end_inset

 the entropy change is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta S & =S_{b}-S_{a}\ge0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is the 
\emph on
second law
\emph default
 of thermodynamics for 
\emph on
closed
\emph default
 systems:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\fbox{\ensuremath{{\displaystyle \Delta S\ge0}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Open system
\emph default
: Let us consider the differential of the entropy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dS_1TdE+1TXdx"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dd S & =\frac{\dd E}{T}+\frac{1}{T}\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}\dd x_{i}\stackrel{\eqref{eq:dW_qs}}{=}\frac{\dd E}{T}-\frac{\dd W_{\text{qs}}}{T}=\\
 & \stackrel{\text{1.law}}{=}\frac{1}{T}\left(\dbar Q+\dbar W-\dbar W_{\text{qs}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So for a quasi-static process holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\fbox{\ensuremath{{\displaystyle \dd S_{\text{qs}}=\frac{\dbar Q_{\text{qs}}}{T}}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

From 
\begin_inset Formula $\dbar W\ge\dbar W_{\text{qs}}$
\end_inset

 follows directly the 
\emph on
second law
\emph default
 of thermodynamics for 
\emph on
open
\emph default
 systems:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\fbox{\ensuremath{{\displaystyle \dd S\ge\frac{\dbar Q}{T}}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Third Law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we investigate the limiting behavior of the entropy for 
\begin_inset Formula $E\to0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When lowering the energy the system approaches the lowest lying states and
 in particular its ground state with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

, there exists usually only one possible state of the system, or, if the
 ground state is degenerate, only a small number of states.
 In this low temperature regime 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\approx f$
\end_inset

 and hence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S & \approx k_{B}\ln\left(f\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

At higher energies holds
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Omega & \sim\left(E-E_{0}\right)^{\gamma f}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S & \approx k_{B}\gamma f\ln\left(E-E_{0}\right)\sim k_{B}\gamma f
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Because we have many degrees of freedom, it follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
k_{B}\ln f & \ll k_{B}\gamma f
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore the following is an excellent approximation:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
stepcounter{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\fbox{\ensuremath{{\displaystyle S\xrightarrow{E\to E_{0}}0}}}\tag{\arabic{chapter}.\arabic{equation}a}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Due to 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{\partial S}{\partial E}>0}$
\end_inset

 follows that with 
\begin_inset Formula $E\to E_{0}$
\end_inset

 also converges 
\begin_inset Formula $T\to T_{0}$
\end_inset

, whereby 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest achievable temperature.
 Now the 
\emph on
third law
\emph default
, also called 
\emph on
Nernst theorem
\emph default
, states:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\fbox{\ensuremath{{\displaystyle S\xrightarrow{T\to T_{0}}0}}}\tag{\arabic{chapter}.\arabic{equation}b}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\emph on
Note
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{k_{B}T} & =\frac{\partial\ln\Omega}{\partial E}\approx\frac{\gamma f}{E-E_{0}}\xrightarrow{E\to E_{0}}\infty\nonumber \\
k_{B}T & \xrightarrow{E\to E_{0}}0\nonumber \\
\Rightarrow\qquad T_{0} & =0\tag{\arabic{chapter}.\arabic{equation}c}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

