\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the order of the particle size.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $r>d$
\end_inset

 the potential is attractive due to (instantaneous) dipole interactions.
 The sketch mimics more realistic potentials (e.g.
 Lennard-Jones potential).
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Due to the attractive potential, the gas exhibits a transition to a liquid
 phase at low temperatures.
 The transition occurs, when 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 is about as large as the attractive potential
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\abs w$
\end_inset

.
 In the following we only consider:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\abs w}{k_{B}T} & \ll1\qquad\text{for }r\gtrapprox d
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e^{-\beta w}-1 & \approx\begin{cases}
-1 & r<d\\
-\beta\omega & r>d
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Rightarrow\qquad B\left(T\right) & \approx2\pi\int_{0}^{d}\dd r\cdot r^{2}+2\pi\beta\int_{d}^{\infty}\dd r\cdot r^{2}\omega\left(r\right):=b-\frac{a}{k_{B}T}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
b & =\frac{2\pi}{3}d^{3}>0 & a & =-2\pi\int_{d}^{\infty}\dd r\cdot r^{2}\omega\left(r\right)>0
\end{align}

\end_inset

Thus we find:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P & =\frac{k_{B}T}{v}\left(1+\frac{B\left(T\right)}{v}\right)=\frac{k_{B}T}{v}\left(1+\frac{b-\frac{a}{k_{B}T}}{v}\right)=\frac{k_{B}T}{v}\left(1+\frac{b}{v}\right)-\frac{a}{v^{2}}\approx\\
 & \approx\frac{k_{B}T}{v}\cdot\frac{1}{1-\frac{b}{v}}-\frac{a}{v^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This yields the equation of the 
\emph on
van-der-Waals gas
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\fbox{\ensuremath{{\displaystyle P=-\frac{a}{v^{2}}+\frac{k_{B}T}{v-b}}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

This gives the corrections to the ideal gas:
\end_layout

