\end{align*}

\end_inset

Using the ansatz
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\vec{E}\left(\vec{r},t\right) & =\vec{E}_{0}e^{\ii\left(\vec{k}\cdot\vec{r}-\omega t\right)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

yields the dispersion relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\omega^{2} & =c^{2}\norm{\vec{k}}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Rightarrow\qquad\fbox{\ensuremath{{\displaystyle \omega=c\norm{\vec{k}}=ck}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

From
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\vec{\nabla}\vec{E} & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\vec{k}\cdot\vec{E}_{0} & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So the electric field is transverse to the direction of propagation, i.e.
 two components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}_{0}$
\end_inset

 are independent.
 This means there are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

two kinds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

