\begin_layout Standard
We are also in the situation that the interaction among the constituents
 is known (electrostatic interaction).
 So the Hamiltonian of a solid then acquires a very general form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{H} & =\hat{T}_{\text{ion}}+\hat{T}_{\text{el}}+\hat{V}_{\text{ee}}+\hat{V}_{\text{ii}}+\hat{V}_{\text{ei}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 are the kinetic energies for the ions and the electrons and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 are the potentials for electron-electron, ion-ion and electron-ion interaction.
 Specifically these look like:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{H} & =-\sum_{\alpha=1}^{M}\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2M_{\alpha}}\nabla_{\alpha}^{2}-\sum_{j=1}^{N}\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\nabla_{j}^{2}+\sum_{j<k}^{N}\frac{e^{2}}{\abs{\vec{r}_{j}-\vec{r}_{k}}}+\sum_{\alpha<\beta}^{M}\frac{Z_{\alpha}Z_{\beta}e^{2}}{\abs{\vec{R}_{\alpha}-\vec{R}_{\beta}}}-\sum_{j}\sum_{\alpha}\frac{Z_{\alpha}e^{2}}{\abs{\vec{r}_{j}-\vec{R}_{\alpha}}}\label{eq:GeneralHamiltonian}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the effective charge number of the ions and due to charge neutrality
 holds 
\begin_inset Formula $N=MZ$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
