\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conductivity tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\vec{E}}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\vec{j}} & =\tilde{\sigma}\tilde{\vec{E}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\varrho}_{e,\text{ind}} & =\tilde{\chi}^{R}\tilde{\varphi}_{\text{ext}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The susceptibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\chi}^{R}$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\varphi}_{\text{ext}}$
\end_inset

.
 This allows to evaluate non-equilibrium quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tilde{\vec{j}},\tilde{\varrho}_{e,\text{ind}}\right)$
\end_inset

 by looking at equilibrium functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tilde{\sigma},\tilde{\chi}^{R},\ldots\right)$
\end_inset

.
