\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider the ionic part of the Hamiltonian of a solid:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{H}_{\text{ion}} & =\hat{T}_{\text{ion}}+\hat{V}_{ii}+\hat{V}_{ei}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{T}_{\text{ion}} & =\sum_{j=1}^{N_{\text{ion}}}\frac{\hat{p}_{j}^{2}}{2m} & \hat{V}_{ii} & =\frac{1}{2}\sum_{l\not=j}\hat{v}_{ii}\left(\vec{R_{l}}-\vec{R_{j}}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

We restrict the discussion here to a monoatomic Bravais lattice.
 Since the atoms can move a little bit around the equilibrium position 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{R}_{j}^{\left(0\right)}$
\end_inset

, we write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vec{R_{j}} & =\vec{R_{j}}^{\left(0\right)}+\vec{u_{j}}\left(t\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

with the displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u_{j}}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 from the equilibrium position.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The 
\emph on
classical
\emph default
 equations of motion for the displacements read:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M\ddot{\vec{u_{j}}}\left(t\right) & =-\frac{\partial V_{ii}}{\partial\vec{u}_{j}}=-\sum_{l}\frac{\partial}{\partial\vec{u}_{j}}v_{ii}\left(\vec{R_{l}}-\vec{R_{j}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In order to simplify this problem, we proceed in steps:
\end_layout

