\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \vec{\epsilon_{k_{1}}},\vec{\epsilon_{k_{2}}},\vec{\epsilon_{k_{3}}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 of vectors (polarization vectors), which diagonalizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mat D\left(\vec{k}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In that basis holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mat D\left(\vec{k}\right)\vec{\epsilon}_{\vec{k},\lambda} & =K_{\vec{k},\lambda}\vec{\epsilon}_{\vec{k},\lambda}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $K_{\vec{k},\lambda}$
\end_inset

 are the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mat D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\epsilon}_{\vec{k},\lambda}\cdot\vec{\epsilon}_{\vec{k},\lambda'}=\delta_{\lambda\lambda'}$
\end_inset

.
